Instead of jumping directly into tools, I focused on building a **clean and scalable network architecture**.


##  Network Overview

- **Internal Network:** SOC-LAB (192.168.10.0/24)
- **Subnet Mask:** 255.255.255.0
- **DNS Server:** 192.168.10.250
- **Internet Access:** NAT (Outbound only)

Each VM is configured with:
- Adapter 1 → NAT (Internet)
- Adapter 2 → Internal Network (SOC-LAB)

## Lab Components

### Core Infrastructure
- Windows Server 2019  
  - Active Directory (AD DS)  
  - DNS  

### Endpoints (Victims)
- Windows 10 → 192.168.10.10  
- Windows 11 → 192.168.10.11  
- macOS → 192.168.10.12  

### User Simulation
- Fedora → 192.168.10.13  

###  Attack Machines
- Kali Linux → 192.168.10.14  
- Parrot Security → 192.168.10.16  

###  Monitoring / SIEM
- Ubuntu Desktop → 192.168.10.15  

### Not Connected (For Now)
- Ubuntu Server (CLI)

## 🧠 Key Design Decisions

- Isolated internal network for realistic attack simulation
- NAT used only for controlled internet access
- Static IP addressing for consistency and control
- Clear segmentation:
  - Victims
  - Attackers
  - Monitoring

